1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,748
Two thirty-two in the afternoon.

2
00:00:01,783 --> 00:00:03,147
May the sixth, twenty-ten.

3
00:00:03,182 --> 00:00:04,895
For most of the world,

4
00:00:04,930 --> 00:00:05,944
nothing is happening.

5
00:00:05,979 --> 00:00:09,091
And then, in the space of a few minutes,

6
00:00:09,126 --> 00:00:12,238
the largest market on
earth begins to fall —

7
00:00:12,273 --> 00:00:14,336
not drift, not slide — fall,

8
00:00:14,371 --> 00:00:17,483
as if the floor underneath
it has been taken

9
00:00:17,518 --> 00:00:18,238
away.

10
00:00:31,711 --> 00:00:33,444
Nearly a thousand points, gone.

11
00:00:33,479 --> 00:00:35,524
Around a trillion dollars in value,

12
00:00:35,559 --> 00:00:38,643
gone. Shares in some of
the most famous companies

13
00:00:38,678 --> 00:00:40,723
in America trade, for a heartbeat,

14
00:00:40,758 --> 00:00:42,110
at a single penny.

15
00:00:42,145 --> 00:00:45,229
And then — almost as fast as it fell

16
00:00:45,264 --> 00:00:46,616
— it comes back.

17
00:00:46,651 --> 00:00:49,042
The whole thing lasts
about thirty-six minutes.

18
00:00:49,077 --> 00:00:51,122
By the end of the day,

19
00:00:51,157 --> 00:00:54,242
the experts will tell
you the market is fine.

20
00:00:54,277 --> 00:00:55,628
The machine corrected itself.

21
00:01:01,411 --> 00:01:04,089
But a question has been
let loose that will

22
00:01:04,124 --> 00:01:05,280
take years to answer.

23
00:01:05,315 --> 00:01:06,768
Because something moved that market.

24
00:01:06,803 --> 00:01:09,446
And when they finally
go looking for what —

25
00:01:09,481 --> 00:01:10,934
they will find a man,

26
00:01:10,969 --> 00:01:13,315
in a bedroom, in a suburb of London,

27
00:01:13,350 --> 00:01:15,993
who did not even like to leave the house.

28
00:01:31,605 --> 00:01:34,332
This is the story of the
most mysterious crash

29
00:01:34,367 --> 00:01:37,060
in market history —
and of the lonely young

30
00:01:37,095 --> 00:01:39,787
man whose name would
end up attached to it.

31
00:01:39,822 --> 00:01:41,606
It is a story about money,

32
00:01:41,641 --> 00:01:43,727
but it is not really about greed.

33
00:01:43,762 --> 00:01:46,455
It is about a machine so fast and so

34
00:01:46,490 --> 00:01:49,182
clever that almost no
one fully understood it —

35
00:01:49,217 --> 00:01:51,909
and how close that machine
came to falling apart,

36
00:01:51,944 --> 00:01:54,334
in front of everyone, in the middle of

37
00:01:54,369 --> 00:01:55,243
an ordinary afternoon.

38
00:02:01,026 --> 00:02:02,477
Over the next half hour,

39
00:02:02,512 --> 00:02:04,507
we are going to do three things.

40
00:02:04,542 --> 00:02:07,119
We are going to show you how a market

41
00:02:07,154 --> 00:02:08,859
this powerful could be this fragile.

42
00:02:08,894 --> 00:02:10,600
We are going to show you,

43
00:02:10,635 --> 00:02:13,211
step by step, exactly
what one trader did —

44
00:02:13,246 --> 00:02:14,952
a trick with a strange name,

45
00:02:14,987 --> 00:02:17,273
that you will understand
completely by the end.

46
00:02:17,308 --> 00:02:19,884
And then we are going to ask the question

47
00:02:19,919 --> 00:02:21,625
the whole case really turns on.

48
00:02:21,660 --> 00:02:23,656
Did one man break the stock market?

49
00:02:23,691 --> 00:02:26,267
Or did he only show us how easily it

50
00:02:26,302 --> 00:02:27,022
could break?.

51
00:02:47,664 --> 00:02:50,497
To understand what happened
in those thirty-six minutes,

52
00:02:50,532 --> 00:02:53,685
you have to forget what you think a stock

53
00:02:53,720 --> 00:02:54,747
market looks like.

54
00:02:54,782 --> 00:02:57,581
There are no men in
coloured jackets shouting

55
00:02:57,616 --> 00:02:58,643
and waving paper.

56
00:02:58,678 --> 00:03:00,414
There haven't been, not really,

57
00:03:00,449 --> 00:03:01,831
for a long time.

58
00:03:01,866 --> 00:03:04,310
The modern market is not a place.

59
00:03:04,345 --> 00:03:06,435
It is a network of machines,

60
00:03:06,470 --> 00:03:09,622
in locked, climate-controlled
rooms, trading with other machines —

61
00:03:09,657 --> 00:03:11,747
buying and selling not in seconds,

62
00:03:11,782 --> 00:03:13,872
but in millionths of a second,

63
00:03:13,907 --> 00:03:17,060
far faster than any human
eye could ever follow.

64
00:03:22,843 --> 00:03:24,597
They are called high-frequency traders.

65
00:03:24,632 --> 00:03:27,753
Algorithms. Programs. And in
the years before our story,

66
00:03:27,788 --> 00:03:30,910
an arms race had broken out among them —

67
00:03:30,945 --> 00:03:32,663
not over who was smartest,

68
00:03:32,698 --> 00:03:34,417
but over who was fastest.

69
00:03:34,452 --> 00:03:37,574
Firms paid fortunes to place
their computers physically closer

70
00:03:37,609 --> 00:03:40,380
to the exchange, so
their orders would arrive

71
00:03:40,415 --> 00:03:42,835
a few millionths of a second sooner.

72
00:03:42,870 --> 00:03:45,991
In this market, that
head start is the whole

73
00:03:46,026 --> 00:03:46,746
game.

74
00:03:52,124 --> 00:03:53,762
And most of the time,

75
00:03:53,797 --> 00:03:55,729
these machines do
something genuinely useful.

76
00:03:55,764 --> 00:03:58,350
They stand ready to buy when you want

77
00:03:58,385 --> 00:04:00,972
to sell, and to sell when you want

78
00:04:01,007 --> 00:04:03,921
to buy. They are the
water the market floats

79
00:04:03,956 --> 00:04:06,870
on. Economists have a gentle word for it —

80
00:04:06,905 --> 00:04:09,819
liquidity. The quiet promise
that there is always someone

81
00:04:09,854 --> 00:04:12,113
on the other side of your trade,

82
00:04:12,148 --> 00:04:14,735
so that whenever you need to get out,

83
00:04:14,770 --> 00:04:15,490
you can.

84
00:04:21,173 --> 00:04:23,710
But here is the truth
underneath that promise,

85
00:04:23,745 --> 00:04:26,565
the one almost nobody
likes to say out loud.

86
00:04:26,600 --> 00:04:28,151
These machines are not loyal.

87
00:04:28,186 --> 00:04:30,371
They feel no duty to be there.

88
00:04:30,406 --> 00:04:33,225
They are not investors;
they do not care what

89
00:04:33,260 --> 00:04:34,494
a company is worth.

90
00:04:34,529 --> 00:04:37,349
They are reading one
thing — the order book,

91
00:04:37,384 --> 00:04:40,203
the live, scrolling
list of who wants to buy

92
00:04:40,238 --> 00:04:43,058
and sell, and at what price — and they

93
00:04:43,093 --> 00:04:44,644
are reacting to it, instantly,

94
00:04:44,679 --> 00:04:47,181
automatically. Feed them
a picture of the market,

95
00:04:47,216 --> 00:04:50,035
and they will move on it before a human

96
00:04:50,070 --> 00:04:50,987
could even blink.

97
00:04:56,769 --> 00:04:59,662
And that is the quiet
miracle the whole market

98
00:04:59,697 --> 00:05:01,912
rests on — and its hidden weakness.

99
00:05:01,947 --> 00:05:04,162
The order book is not just data.

100
00:05:04,197 --> 00:05:06,412
It is a kind of collective belief,

101
00:05:06,447 --> 00:05:09,305
a shared picture of what
everyone else is about

102
00:05:09,340 --> 00:05:10,269
to do next.

103
00:05:10,304 --> 00:05:12,197
The machines trust that
picture completely,

104
00:05:12,232 --> 00:05:14,769
because trusting it
instantly is the only way

105
00:05:14,804 --> 00:05:15,733
to stay fast.

106
00:05:15,768 --> 00:05:17,662
But a picture can be painted.

107
00:05:17,697 --> 00:05:20,233
And a market that runs at the speed

108
00:05:20,268 --> 00:05:22,483
of light, on trust in a picture,

109
00:05:22,518 --> 00:05:25,376
can be fooled at the speed of light too.

110
00:05:31,159 --> 00:05:32,788
Which raises a dangerous question,

111
00:05:32,823 --> 00:05:35,720
one that, in twenty-ten,
almost no one was asking

112
00:05:35,755 --> 00:05:38,653
out loud. What if the picture were a lie?

113
00:05:38,688 --> 00:05:41,259
What if you could show
the machines something

114
00:05:41,294 --> 00:05:43,866
that wasn't true — a flood of buyers

115
00:05:43,901 --> 00:05:46,798
that didn't exist, a
wall of sellers who were

116
00:05:46,833 --> 00:05:49,730
never really there —
and simply let their own

117
00:05:49,765 --> 00:05:51,685
speed and logic do the rest?.

118
00:05:57,467 --> 00:05:59,816
In a small bedroom in west London,

119
00:05:59,851 --> 00:06:02,165
one man was not asking the question.

120
00:06:02,200 --> 00:06:04,514
He had stopped asking it years before.

121
00:06:04,549 --> 00:06:06,863
He was already living, every single day,

122
00:06:06,898 --> 00:06:07,870
inside the answer.

123
00:06:13,653 --> 00:06:15,803
His name is Navinder Singh Sarao.

124
00:06:15,838 --> 00:06:17,594
He grows up in Hounslow,

125
00:06:17,629 --> 00:06:19,743
on the western edge of London,

126
00:06:19,778 --> 00:06:22,251
directly under the flight
path into Heathrow,

127
00:06:22,286 --> 00:06:25,117
where the planes pass
overhead every ninety seconds

128
00:06:25,152 --> 00:06:28,341
or so — close enough
to rattle the windows,

129
00:06:28,376 --> 00:06:29,774
regular as a heartbeat.

130
00:06:29,809 --> 00:06:31,566
He is brilliant with numbers,

131
00:06:31,601 --> 00:06:32,999
and uneasy with people.

132
00:06:33,034 --> 00:06:36,223
Years later, doctors will
diagnose him with severe autism.

133
00:06:47,210 --> 00:06:49,985
He does not learn to trade in a bank,

134
00:06:50,020 --> 00:06:52,143
or a glass tower in the city.

135
00:06:52,178 --> 00:06:53,992
He learns it on a screen,

136
00:06:54,027 --> 00:06:56,459
in a back office and then at home,

137
00:06:56,494 --> 00:06:59,233
and he turns out to be
astonishingly good at

138
00:06:59,268 --> 00:07:02,008
it — fast, fearless, able to feel the flow

139
00:07:02,043 --> 00:07:04,474
of the market the way a kayaker feels

140
00:07:04,509 --> 00:07:06,016
a river, reading the current,

141
00:07:06,051 --> 00:07:08,482
the pull, the places where it is about

142
00:07:08,517 --> 00:07:11,257
to turn. People who traded
near him describe it

143
00:07:11,292 --> 00:07:12,798
as a kind of genius.

144
00:07:18,580 --> 00:07:21,679
And he could have had all of it —

145
00:07:21,714 --> 00:07:23,745
the office, the salary, the city,

146
00:07:23,780 --> 00:07:26,155
the noise. He does not want them.

147
00:07:26,190 --> 00:07:27,533
He wants the room.

148
00:07:27,568 --> 00:07:29,254
So he trades from home,

149
00:07:29,289 --> 00:07:31,665
from the bedroom in his parents' house,

150
00:07:31,700 --> 00:07:34,419
in a tracksuit, the
curtains often drawn against

151
00:07:34,454 --> 00:07:37,518
the afternoon. And there is
something almost unbearable about

152
00:07:37,553 --> 00:07:40,273
the picture: downstairs,
his mother is making dinner;

153
00:07:40,308 --> 00:07:43,027
upstairs, her son is moving more money in

154
00:07:43,062 --> 00:07:45,782
a single afternoon than
most people will see

155
00:07:45,817 --> 00:07:46,815
in a lifetime.

156
00:07:52,598 --> 00:07:55,263
And here is the detail
that everyone who meets

157
00:07:55,298 --> 00:07:57,632
him remembers — the detail that makes this

158
00:07:57,667 --> 00:07:59,704
a tragedy and not just a crime.

159
00:07:59,739 --> 00:08:02,369
He does not seem to care about the money.

160
00:08:02,404 --> 00:08:04,738
Not as a pose, not as false modesty.

161
00:08:04,773 --> 00:08:06,219
He doesn't buy the cars,

162
00:08:06,254 --> 00:08:08,884
or the house, or the life the money could

163
00:08:08,919 --> 00:08:11,549
have bought. People who
knew him describe a man

164
00:08:11,584 --> 00:08:14,214
trading the way a child
plays an arcade game

165
00:08:14,249 --> 00:08:15,694
— locked onto the screen,

166
00:08:15,729 --> 00:08:17,767
hour after hour, trying, over and over,

167
00:08:17,802 --> 00:08:19,543
to beat his own high score.

168
00:08:19,578 --> 00:08:22,208
An autism specialist will
later put it as plainly

169
00:08:22,243 --> 00:08:23,689
as it can be put:

170
00:08:23,724 --> 00:08:26,354
his lack of any interest in the money he

171
00:08:26,389 --> 00:08:27,834
earned was not an act.

172
00:08:27,869 --> 00:08:29,611
It was simply who he was.

173
00:08:35,393 --> 00:08:37,399
But to beat the high score,

174
00:08:37,434 --> 00:08:38,737
he wants an edge.

175
00:08:38,772 --> 00:08:41,746
And he has become convinced
that the market is

176
00:08:41,781 --> 00:08:43,752
rigged — not against him personally,

177
00:08:43,787 --> 00:08:45,424
but by the fastest machines,

178
00:08:45,459 --> 00:08:48,433
the ones that always
seem to get there first,

179
00:08:48,468 --> 00:08:50,105
the ones that, to him,

180
00:08:50,140 --> 00:08:52,112
are skimming a little from everyone,

181
00:08:52,147 --> 00:08:54,787
all day long, simply
because they are quicker.

182
00:08:54,822 --> 00:08:56,793
He doesn't want to join them.

183
00:08:56,828 --> 00:08:58,465
He wants to beat them.

184
00:08:58,500 --> 00:09:01,474
So he decides to fight
the machines on their

185
00:09:01,509 --> 00:09:03,480
own ground, with their own weapon:

186
00:09:03,515 --> 00:09:05,821
speed. He takes a piece of ordinary,

187
00:09:05,856 --> 00:09:08,496
commercial trading software,
the kind anyone could buy,

188
00:09:08,531 --> 00:09:10,502
and he begins to rewrite it.

189
00:09:16,285 --> 00:09:19,559
What he builds is simple
to describe and devastating

190
00:09:19,594 --> 00:09:22,833
to watch. A program that
can place enormous orders

191
00:09:22,868 --> 00:09:25,016
— and then pull them back,

192
00:09:25,051 --> 00:09:28,290
automatically, in an instant,
before any human and almost

193
00:09:28,325 --> 00:09:30,109
any machine can take them.

194
00:09:30,144 --> 00:09:33,383
Orders that look, for
a fraction of a second,

195
00:09:33,418 --> 00:09:35,565
completely real. Orders that were never,

196
00:09:35,600 --> 00:09:38,112
for one moment, meant to be filled.

197
00:09:38,147 --> 00:09:40,295
There is a name for this,

198
00:09:40,330 --> 00:09:42,841
a name the law will eventually use.

199
00:09:42,876 --> 00:09:44,660
They will call it spoofing.

200
00:09:50,442 --> 00:09:51,907
Here is how it works.

201
00:09:51,942 --> 00:09:54,252
And the genius of it — the cruelty

202
00:09:54,287 --> 00:09:56,890
of it — is that once you see it,

203
00:09:56,925 --> 00:09:58,062
you cannot unsee it.

204
00:09:58,097 --> 00:09:58,941
So watch closely.

205
00:10:04,724 --> 00:10:06,453
Picture the order book again.

206
00:10:06,488 --> 00:10:09,218
On one side, everyone who wants to buy,

207
00:10:09,253 --> 00:10:11,293
and the prices they will pay.

208
00:10:11,328 --> 00:10:14,059
On the other, everyone who wants to sell,

209
00:10:14,094 --> 00:10:16,133
and the prices they will accept.

210
00:10:16,168 --> 00:10:18,553
The machines are watching
this book constantly,

211
00:10:18,588 --> 00:10:20,282
and they reason, quite logically:

212
00:10:20,317 --> 00:10:23,393
if a huge new wall of
sellers suddenly appears,

213
00:10:23,428 --> 00:10:25,467
far bigger than everything around it,

214
00:10:25,502 --> 00:10:27,887
then the price is about to drop.

215
00:10:27,922 --> 00:10:29,962
The smart move, the safe move,

216
00:10:29,997 --> 00:10:32,728
is to sell now — to get out

217
00:10:32,763 --> 00:10:34,802
a half-second ahead of everyone else,

218
00:10:34,837 --> 00:10:35,839
before the fall.

219
00:10:41,621 --> 00:10:43,676
So Sarao shows them a wall.

220
00:10:43,711 --> 00:10:46,759
Using his program, he
places sell orders so large

221
00:10:46,794 --> 00:10:49,842
they dwarf everything
else in the book — tens

222
00:10:49,877 --> 00:10:51,555
of millions of dollars' worth,

223
00:10:51,590 --> 00:10:53,953
stacked, layered, just
above the current price.

224
00:10:53,988 --> 00:10:55,666
The machines see the wall.

225
00:10:55,701 --> 00:10:58,749
They believe it, because
they have no way not

226
00:10:58,784 --> 00:11:01,832
to. And they do exactly
what their logic demands.

227
00:11:01,867 --> 00:11:03,545
They begin to sell, fast,

228
00:11:03,580 --> 00:11:05,600
to get ahead of the drop.

229
00:11:05,635 --> 00:11:08,683
And the price begins to fall — pushed down

230
00:11:08,718 --> 00:11:10,396
not by anyone actually selling,

231
00:11:10,431 --> 00:11:13,479
but by the simple fear
that selling is coming.

232
00:11:24,466 --> 00:11:26,048
And that is the moment.

233
00:11:26,083 --> 00:11:28,896
As the price slides
toward the level where he

234
00:11:28,931 --> 00:11:31,428
secretly wants to buy,
Sarao cancels the wall.

235
00:11:31,463 --> 00:11:33,327
In the blink of an eye,

236
00:11:33,362 --> 00:11:36,175
the orders that frightened
the whole market simply vanish

237
00:11:36,210 --> 00:11:39,023
— because they were
never meant to be filled.

238
00:11:39,058 --> 00:11:40,289
They were a ghost.

239
00:11:40,324 --> 00:11:42,821
And in the empty space they leave behind,

240
00:11:42,856 --> 00:11:45,352
at the low price his own ghost created,

241
00:11:45,387 --> 00:11:46,618
he buys. For real.

242
00:11:52,401 --> 00:11:55,310
Then he turns the entire thing upside down

243
00:11:55,345 --> 00:11:57,856
to sell. Show a wall of buyers,

244
00:11:57,891 --> 00:12:00,038
lift the price, pull the wall,

245
00:12:00,073 --> 00:12:02,584
sell high. Show a wall of sellers,

246
00:12:02,619 --> 00:12:04,766
drop the price, pull the wall,

247
00:12:04,801 --> 00:12:05,857
buy low. Again.

248
00:12:05,892 --> 00:12:09,130
And again. And again — not for a day,

249
00:12:09,165 --> 00:12:10,221
but for years.

250
00:12:10,256 --> 00:12:12,039
By his own later admission,

251
00:12:12,074 --> 00:12:15,313
this earns him at least
twelve point eight million

252
00:12:15,348 --> 00:12:17,858
dollars. Regulators will
say the true figure,

253
00:12:17,893 --> 00:12:20,404
across all his trading, was far higher.

254
00:12:26,186 --> 00:12:28,130
Think about what that means.

255
00:12:28,165 --> 00:12:31,629
He is, in effect, lying to the market —

256
00:12:31,664 --> 00:12:33,962
not in words, but in orders.

257
00:12:33,997 --> 00:12:36,295
And the market — that vast,

258
00:12:36,330 --> 00:12:39,794
rational, lightning-fast machine
that holds the savings of millions

259
00:12:39,829 --> 00:12:41,738
of people — believes him.

260
00:12:41,773 --> 00:12:42,904
Every single time.

261
00:12:48,687 --> 00:12:51,734
And the strangest part
is how invisible it all

262
00:12:51,769 --> 00:12:53,765
is. There is no broken window,

263
00:12:53,800 --> 00:12:56,135
no alarm, no smoke — just numbers,

264
00:12:56,170 --> 00:12:58,166
appearing and vanishing
faster than thought,

265
00:12:58,201 --> 00:12:59,859
on screens in locked rooms.

266
00:12:59,894 --> 00:13:02,906
To almost everyone watching
the market in those years,

267
00:13:02,941 --> 00:13:04,598
nothing looks wrong at all.

268
00:13:04,633 --> 00:13:07,306
The wall goes up, the wall comes down,

269
00:13:07,341 --> 00:13:10,353
and only the man who built it ever knows

270
00:13:10,388 --> 00:13:12,046
it was never really there.

271
00:13:17,828 --> 00:13:19,508
For most of those years,

272
00:13:19,543 --> 00:13:21,188
almost no one even notices.

273
00:13:21,223 --> 00:13:23,541
A single man, in a single bedroom,

274
00:13:23,576 --> 00:13:26,565
is quietly leaning his whole
weight against the most

275
00:13:26,600 --> 00:13:28,245
sophisticated financial system ever built.

276
00:13:28,280 --> 00:13:30,262
And the system, it turns out,

277
00:13:30,297 --> 00:13:32,614
leans. It bends right where he pushes.

278
00:13:32,649 --> 00:13:35,638
The only question left
— the one nobody has

279
00:13:35,673 --> 00:13:38,327
thought to ask — is what happens if,

280
00:13:38,362 --> 00:13:41,015
one day, he leans on it at exactly

281
00:13:41,050 --> 00:13:42,023
the wrong moment.

282
00:13:47,806 --> 00:13:50,529
May the sixth, twenty-ten,
does not begin as

283
00:13:50,564 --> 00:13:53,251
a catastrophe. It begins as a nervous day.

284
00:13:53,286 --> 00:13:55,634
On the other side of the world,

285
00:13:55,669 --> 00:13:57,676
Greece is sliding toward
financial collapse;

286
00:13:57,711 --> 00:14:00,738
there are riots in the
streets of Athens on

287
00:14:00,773 --> 00:14:03,801
the evening news; and the
markets everywhere are jittery,

288
00:14:03,836 --> 00:14:06,864
on edge, looking for
a reason to be afraid.

289
00:14:06,899 --> 00:14:08,906
Fear is already in the room.

290
00:14:08,941 --> 00:14:10,608
It only needs a push.

291
00:14:16,390 --> 00:14:18,406
Into that fear, that morning,

292
00:14:18,441 --> 00:14:20,825
Navinder Sarao switches on his program.

293
00:14:20,860 --> 00:14:24,454
Investigators will later
say that on this single day,

294
00:14:24,489 --> 00:14:27,679
he places, modifies, and
cancels orders worth billions

295
00:14:27,714 --> 00:14:30,501
of dollars — a vast ghost wall,

296
00:14:30,536 --> 00:14:33,324
leaning on the market, on and off,

297
00:14:33,359 --> 00:14:34,130
for hours.

298
00:14:39,913 --> 00:14:41,695
But he is not alone.

299
00:14:41,730 --> 00:14:44,547
And this is the part the simple version

300
00:14:44,582 --> 00:14:46,686
of the story always leaves out.

301
00:14:46,721 --> 00:14:49,894
Somewhere else entirely, for
reasons that are completely ordinary

302
00:14:49,929 --> 00:14:52,746
and completely legal, a
large investment firm decides

303
00:14:52,781 --> 00:14:55,241
to sell — to hedge a position,

304
00:14:55,276 --> 00:14:56,311
to protect itself.

305
00:14:56,346 --> 00:14:58,093
It is an enormous order:

306
00:14:58,128 --> 00:15:01,301
seventy-five thousand futures contracts,
more than four billion dollars'

307
00:15:01,336 --> 00:15:04,510
worth, and it is fed into the market not

308
00:15:04,545 --> 00:15:07,718
by a person, but by an algorithm of its

309
00:15:07,753 --> 00:15:10,570
own. An algorithm given
one instruction — sell,

310
00:15:10,605 --> 00:15:13,421
and sell quickly — without much regard for

311
00:15:13,456 --> 00:15:16,630
the price it gets, or the damage it might

312
00:15:16,665 --> 00:15:18,412
do on the way down.

313
00:15:24,195 --> 00:15:27,373
So now there are two
great weights pressing on

314
00:15:27,408 --> 00:15:30,197
the same fragile market
at the same moment.

315
00:15:30,232 --> 00:15:33,022
One a careless giant,
selling four billion dollars

316
00:15:33,057 --> 00:15:34,787
as fast as it can.

317
00:15:34,822 --> 00:15:37,259
One a deliberate ghost, leaning and lying.

318
00:15:37,294 --> 00:15:40,083
And all around them, the
high-frequency machines —

319
00:15:40,118 --> 00:15:43,261
the water the market
floats on — are watching

320
00:15:43,296 --> 00:15:45,379
the order book fill with sell,

321
00:15:45,414 --> 00:15:48,204
sell, sell, and they
are beginning to flinch.

322
00:15:59,190 --> 00:16:01,453
At two thirty-two in the afternoon,

323
00:16:01,488 --> 00:16:04,847
something gives. The machines
that promised to always be

324
00:16:04,882 --> 00:16:08,241
there do the one thing no one had planned

325
00:16:08,276 --> 00:16:11,635
for, the one thing the whole
system quietly depended

326
00:16:11,670 --> 00:16:13,143
on them never doing.

327
00:16:13,178 --> 00:16:14,275
They step back.

328
00:16:14,310 --> 00:16:15,406
All at once.

329
00:16:15,441 --> 00:16:18,046
To protect themselves
from a falling market,

330
00:16:18,081 --> 00:16:19,555
they simply stop buying.

331
00:16:19,590 --> 00:16:21,063
And the floor disappears.

332
00:16:26,846 --> 00:16:28,485
Now prices do not fall.

333
00:16:28,520 --> 00:16:30,123
They collapse, into a vacuum.

334
00:16:30,158 --> 00:16:33,073
With almost no machines
left willing to catch them,

335
00:16:33,108 --> 00:16:36,022
shares in giant, healthy, world-famous
companies plunge toward nothing.

336
00:16:36,057 --> 00:16:37,661
For a few astonishing seconds,

337
00:16:37,696 --> 00:16:40,610
you could have bought a share of a company

338
00:16:40,645 --> 00:16:43,560
worth tens of billions
of dollars for a single

339
00:16:43,595 --> 00:16:46,509
penny — not because anything
real had changed about

340
00:16:46,544 --> 00:16:48,803
that company, not because of any news,

341
00:16:48,838 --> 00:16:50,769
but because, for a few minutes,

342
00:16:50,804 --> 00:16:52,736
on the whole of the market,

343
00:16:52,771 --> 00:16:55,685
there was simply no one on the other side.

344
00:17:01,467 --> 00:17:04,733
And it is not only numbers on a screen.

345
00:17:04,768 --> 00:17:07,999
All over the country, ordinary
people have left standing

346
00:17:08,034 --> 00:17:10,177
instructions with their brokers — sell,

347
00:17:10,212 --> 00:17:13,443
automatically, if my stock
ever falls below this price

348
00:17:13,478 --> 00:17:16,709
— small, sensible safety
nets meant to protect them.

349
00:17:16,744 --> 00:17:19,612
In those thirty-six minutes,
as prices fall through

350
00:17:19,647 --> 00:17:21,426
the floor, those instructions fire,

351
00:17:21,461 --> 00:17:24,692
all at once, selling people's
savings into the very

352
00:17:24,727 --> 00:17:27,596
bottom of the crash, at the worst prices

353
00:17:27,631 --> 00:17:28,684
of the day.

354
00:17:28,719 --> 00:17:30,862
The panic of the machines becomes,

355
00:17:30,897 --> 00:17:34,128
for a few minutes, the
real and lasting loss

356
00:17:34,163 --> 00:17:36,668
of people who were not even watching.

357
00:17:42,451 --> 00:17:44,198
And then the safeties trip.

358
00:17:44,233 --> 00:17:46,643
Automatic circuit breakers,
built for exactly this,

359
00:17:46,678 --> 00:17:48,390
begin to fire; exchanges pause;

360
00:17:48,425 --> 00:17:50,486
the panic runs out of room.

361
00:17:50,521 --> 00:17:52,233
Cautiously, the machines come back.

362
00:17:52,268 --> 00:17:53,281
The water returns.

363
00:17:53,316 --> 00:17:56,425
And the market floats
again — climbing back out

364
00:17:56,460 --> 00:17:59,569
of the hole almost as violently as it fell

365
00:17:59,604 --> 00:18:00,967
in. It is over.

366
00:18:01,002 --> 00:18:03,063
A trillion dollars has been lost,

367
00:18:03,098 --> 00:18:05,159
and found, inside a single hour.

368
00:18:05,194 --> 00:18:08,303
And the most powerful
financial system on earth has

369
00:18:08,338 --> 00:18:11,447
just learned something about
itself that it would very

370
00:18:11,482 --> 00:18:13,194
much prefer not to know.

371
00:18:18,976 --> 00:18:20,257
Afterward comes the autopsy.

372
00:18:20,292 --> 00:18:23,138
And this is where the story refuses to be

373
00:18:23,173 --> 00:18:25,380
simple — where you have to resist,

374
00:18:25,415 --> 00:18:27,621
with both hands, the ending you want.

375
00:18:27,656 --> 00:18:29,222
Because we want a villain.

376
00:18:29,257 --> 00:18:31,143
A villain would be a relief.

377
00:18:36,926 --> 00:18:39,189
The first official report, months later,

378
00:18:39,224 --> 00:18:41,452
points mostly at the careless giant:

379
00:18:41,487 --> 00:18:44,847
that four-billion-dollar sell program,
dumped by an unthinking algorithm

380
00:18:44,882 --> 00:18:47,864
into a market that had grown too thin

381
00:18:47,899 --> 00:18:48,996
to absorb it.

382
00:18:49,031 --> 00:18:52,390
It barely mentions a
trader in London at all.

383
00:18:52,426 --> 00:18:55,785
Then other studies look harder
at the high-frequency machines,

384
00:18:55,820 --> 00:18:58,048
and reach a careful, important conclusion:

385
00:18:58,083 --> 00:19:01,443
the machines did not cause the crash — but

386
00:19:01,478 --> 00:19:04,838
they deepened it, by
all racing for the exit

387
00:19:04,873 --> 00:19:07,855
at once, by demanding to get out first.

388
00:19:20,577 --> 00:19:22,656
And then, almost five years later,

389
00:19:22,691 --> 00:19:25,775
investigators trace the
ghost back to its source —

390
00:19:25,810 --> 00:19:27,507
to the bedroom in Hounslow.

391
00:19:27,542 --> 00:19:29,586
They say his wall, that morning,

392
00:19:29,621 --> 00:19:32,705
was part of the imbalance
that tipped the market

393
00:19:32,740 --> 00:19:35,477
over. In their words, he was
significantly responsible

394
00:19:35,512 --> 00:19:38,596
for the order imbalances
that helped trigger the fall.

395
00:19:51,317 --> 00:19:54,493
How they found him at all is its own

396
00:19:54,528 --> 00:19:57,668
quiet story. The ghost had
left almost no fingerprints;

397
00:19:57,703 --> 00:20:00,844
his orders had simply
vanished the instant they did

398
00:20:00,879 --> 00:20:04,019
their work. It took
years of patient effort —

399
00:20:04,054 --> 00:20:07,195
sifting back through the
raw data of that single

400
00:20:07,230 --> 00:20:10,017
afternoon, through billions
of messages — to trace

401
00:20:10,052 --> 00:20:13,193
the vanished orders through
the noise to one account,

402
00:20:13,228 --> 00:20:14,957
and one house, in Hounslow.

403
00:20:14,992 --> 00:20:18,133
The most mysterious crash in
market history was unraveled,

404
00:20:18,168 --> 00:20:20,250
in the end, not by speed,

405
00:20:20,285 --> 00:20:23,425
but by someone slow and
stubborn enough to keep

406
00:20:23,460 --> 00:20:24,180
looking.

407
00:20:41,704 --> 00:20:44,630
But notice the words they actually use.

408
00:20:44,665 --> 00:20:46,302
Part of. Contributed to.

409
00:20:46,337 --> 00:20:47,555
Helped to tip.

410
00:20:47,590 --> 00:20:49,645
Significantly responsible
for the imbalance.

411
00:20:49,680 --> 00:20:52,153
Not, anywhere, in any serious account:

412
00:20:52,188 --> 00:20:53,407
caused it, alone.

413
00:20:53,442 --> 00:20:57,169
Because the honest answer
is harder than a single

414
00:20:57,204 --> 00:20:59,258
villain, and far more frightening.

415
00:20:59,293 --> 00:21:01,348
A careless four-billion-dollar sell order.

416
00:21:01,383 --> 00:21:04,692
A swarm of machines all
protecting themselves at

417
00:21:04,727 --> 00:21:05,946
the same instant.

418
00:21:05,981 --> 00:21:09,290
A world already sick
with fear over Greece.

419
00:21:09,325 --> 00:21:13,051
And yes — a ghost in the order book,

420
00:21:13,086 --> 00:21:15,559
pushing at exactly the wrong moment.

421
00:21:15,594 --> 00:21:18,067
All of it, together, at once,

422
00:21:18,102 --> 00:21:20,574
on a market that had quietly,

423
00:21:20,609 --> 00:21:24,336
invisibly, become too fast
and too fragile for anyone,

424
00:21:24,371 --> 00:21:26,008
anywhere, to fully see.

425
00:21:31,791 --> 00:21:34,499
Which leaves us with the
question this whole story

426
00:21:34,534 --> 00:21:36,906
has been circling from
the very first second.

427
00:21:36,941 --> 00:21:39,312
If a system this powerful can be pushed

428
00:21:39,347 --> 00:21:42,020
to the edge of collapse by a lie told

429
00:21:42,055 --> 00:21:44,728
in orders that were never even real — then

430
00:21:44,763 --> 00:21:46,232
what, exactly, broke that day?

431
00:21:46,267 --> 00:21:48,037
The man who told the lie?

432
00:21:48,072 --> 00:21:50,745
Or the machine that could
not tell the difference

433
00:21:50,780 --> 00:21:52,550
between a phantom and the truth?.

434
00:21:58,332 --> 00:21:59,757
The law, in the end,

435
00:21:59,792 --> 00:22:02,322
does not get to answer that with a shrug.

436
00:22:02,357 --> 00:22:04,601
The law has to choose someone to hold.

437
00:22:04,636 --> 00:22:07,166
And of all the forces in that market on

438
00:22:07,201 --> 00:22:08,591
that afternoon — the algorithms,

439
00:22:08,626 --> 00:22:11,156
the firms, the fear — only one of them

440
00:22:11,191 --> 00:22:13,435
was a person, who had made a choice,

441
00:22:13,470 --> 00:22:15,145
and broken a rule, on purpose.

442
00:22:15,180 --> 00:22:17,140
And so the law chooses the man.

443
00:22:22,923 --> 00:22:25,465
In twenty-fifteen, five
years after the crash,

444
00:22:25,500 --> 00:22:27,280
they finally come for him.

445
00:22:27,315 --> 00:22:30,548
He is arrested at his
parents' house in London

446
00:22:30,583 --> 00:22:33,452
— the same house, the same street under

447
00:22:33,487 --> 00:22:36,720
the flight path — and
the United States asks

448
00:22:36,755 --> 00:22:39,261
for him by name: the Hounslow day-trader,

449
00:22:39,296 --> 00:22:42,529
the headlines now say, who
helped trigger a trillion-dollar

450
00:22:42,564 --> 00:22:43,981
crash from his bedroom.

451
00:22:44,016 --> 00:22:46,160
He fights the extradition for months.

452
00:22:46,195 --> 00:22:46,915
He loses.

453
00:22:52,668 --> 00:22:55,415
And when investigators
finally open up his life

454
00:22:55,450 --> 00:22:57,819
and look at what is actually there,

455
00:22:57,854 --> 00:22:59,536
they find something almost unbearable.

456
00:22:59,571 --> 00:23:02,627
The fortune — the tens of millions he had

457
00:23:02,662 --> 00:23:05,717
won from the fastest
machines on earth — is

458
00:23:05,752 --> 00:23:07,091
mostly gone. Not spent.

459
00:23:07,126 --> 00:23:10,182
Taken. The man who could
fool the most sophisticated

460
00:23:10,217 --> 00:23:13,272
market ever built had
himself turned out to be

461
00:23:13,307 --> 00:23:16,019
an easy mark: he had handed his money,

462
00:23:16,054 --> 00:23:18,423
almost all of it, to con men,

463
00:23:18,458 --> 00:23:21,171
to bogus investments, to
an outright fraud built

464
00:23:21,206 --> 00:23:23,574
to part trusting people
from their savings.

465
00:23:23,609 --> 00:23:25,635
He had beaten the high score,

466
00:23:25,670 --> 00:23:28,725
over and over, for years — and kept almost

467
00:23:28,760 --> 00:23:30,099
none of the points.

468
00:23:35,882 --> 00:23:37,693
In twenty-sixteen, he pleads guilty.

469
00:23:37,728 --> 00:23:40,952
Not to causing the crash — to two specific

470
00:23:40,987 --> 00:23:43,124
crimes: one count of wire fraud,

471
00:23:43,159 --> 00:23:44,935
and one count of spoofing.

472
00:23:44,970 --> 00:23:48,194
He agrees to hand back nearly
thirteen million dollars.

473
00:23:48,229 --> 00:23:51,453
And then he does something
the authorities did not

474
00:23:51,488 --> 00:23:53,263
have to ask twice for.

475
00:23:53,298 --> 00:23:55,798
He cooperates, completely
— sitting with them,

476
00:23:55,833 --> 00:23:59,057
explaining his own methods,
helping the people who caught

477
00:23:59,092 --> 00:24:02,316
him understand the very
thing he had spent years

478
00:24:02,351 --> 00:24:03,071
perfecting.

479
00:24:08,460 --> 00:24:10,465
There is a temptation, telling this,

480
00:24:10,500 --> 00:24:13,137
to turn him into a folk hero —

481
00:24:13,172 --> 00:24:16,144
the lone genius who beat
the machines at their

482
00:24:16,179 --> 00:24:17,481
own game. Resist that.

483
00:24:17,516 --> 00:24:19,485
What he did broke the law,

484
00:24:19,520 --> 00:24:21,824
and he admitted it; real money moved,

485
00:24:21,859 --> 00:24:24,831
and real people, somewhere,
were on the other side

486
00:24:24,866 --> 00:24:27,838
of it. But there is no honesty in making

487
00:24:27,873 --> 00:24:29,174
him a monster either.

488
00:24:29,209 --> 00:24:31,179
The truth is smaller, and sadder:

489
00:24:31,214 --> 00:24:33,851
a brilliant, lonely
man, chasing a number on

490
00:24:33,886 --> 00:24:36,858
a screen, who understood
the rule he broke better

491
00:24:36,893 --> 00:24:39,865
than almost anyone — and
never seemed to grasp,

492
00:24:39,900 --> 00:24:42,872
or to care, what the
number was actually worth.

493
00:24:48,655 --> 00:24:51,825
And at his sentencing, the
prosecutors do something genuinely

494
00:24:51,860 --> 00:24:54,291
rare. They ask the judge for mercy.

495
00:24:54,326 --> 00:24:56,052
They point to his cooperation.

496
00:24:56,087 --> 00:24:59,223
And they point to the
diagnosis — the severe

497
00:24:59,258 --> 00:25:00,984
autism that, an expert testifies,

498
00:25:01,019 --> 00:25:03,097
was woven through the whole story:

499
00:25:03,132 --> 00:25:05,563
that made the money meaningless to him,

500
00:25:05,598 --> 00:25:08,734
and the game everything;
that helps explain a man

501
00:25:08,769 --> 00:25:11,904
who could read a global
market like a book,

502
00:25:11,939 --> 00:25:15,074
and yet could be robbed
blind by the oldest

503
00:25:15,109 --> 00:25:16,483
tricks in the world.

504
00:25:16,518 --> 00:25:19,301
He had faced the real
possibility of years,

505
00:25:19,336 --> 00:25:21,767
even a decade, in an American prison.

506
00:25:27,549 --> 00:25:30,433
In twenty-twenty, the judge
sentences him to no further

507
00:25:30,468 --> 00:25:31,394
prison at all.

508
00:25:31,429 --> 00:25:33,637
A single year — served at home.

509
00:25:33,672 --> 00:25:35,560
In the bedroom, more or less,

510
00:25:35,595 --> 00:25:37,162
where the whole thing began.

511
00:25:57,979 --> 00:25:59,367
The money is gone.

512
00:25:59,402 --> 00:26:00,755
The program is gone.

513
00:26:00,790 --> 00:26:03,877
And the man goes quietly
back to an ordinary

514
00:26:03,912 --> 00:26:05,612
house under the flight path,

515
00:26:05,647 --> 00:26:07,346
the planes still passing overhead,

516
00:26:07,381 --> 00:26:09,775
every ninety seconds,
regular as a heartbeat.

517
00:26:15,558 --> 00:26:17,983
We wanted this story to have a villain,

518
00:26:18,018 --> 00:26:19,499
because a villain is comforting.

519
00:26:19,534 --> 00:26:21,621
A villain means the system was sound,

520
00:26:21,656 --> 00:26:23,440
and one bad man broke it,

521
00:26:23,475 --> 00:26:25,865
and now the bad man has been caught,

522
00:26:25,900 --> 00:26:27,381
and so we are safe.

523
00:26:27,416 --> 00:26:29,806
But that is not quite what happened here.

524
00:26:29,841 --> 00:26:32,534
What happened is that a lonely man who did

525
00:26:32,569 --> 00:26:35,263
not care about money,
playing a game in his

526
00:26:35,298 --> 00:26:37,991
bedroom, reached out one
finger and touched the great

527
00:26:38,026 --> 00:26:40,416
machine of the market — and the machine,

528
00:26:40,451 --> 00:26:41,629
for thirty-six minutes, shook.

529
00:26:41,664 --> 00:26:43,448
He did not do it alone.

530
00:26:43,483 --> 00:26:46,176
But he showed us, more
clearly than any report

531
00:26:46,211 --> 00:26:48,298
ever could, how little it might take.

532
00:26:54,080 --> 00:26:57,095
And the market is faster now than it was

533
00:26:57,130 --> 00:26:59,104
that day. Faster, and more automatic,

534
00:26:59,139 --> 00:27:02,119
and more sure of itself than ever — more

535
00:27:02,154 --> 00:27:05,133
machines, more speed, more
weight resting on the quiet

536
00:27:05,168 --> 00:27:07,813
promise that the water
will always be there.

537
00:27:07,848 --> 00:27:09,823
We are told it is rational.

538
00:27:09,858 --> 00:27:11,832
We are told it is safe.

539
00:27:11,867 --> 00:27:13,507
But somewhere inside it, still,

540
00:27:13,542 --> 00:27:15,852
is the memory of a single afternoon,

541
00:27:15,887 --> 00:27:18,866
when the most rational
machine ever built looked at

542
00:27:18,901 --> 00:27:20,876
a ghost — and believed it.

543
00:27:26,659 --> 00:27:29,312
So here is the question we will leave you

544
00:27:29,347 --> 00:27:31,671
with. The next time the floor disappears —

545
00:27:31,706 --> 00:27:34,324
and one day, it will — who do you

546
00:27:34,359 --> 00:27:36,093
think will be holding the ghost?

547
00:27:36,128 --> 00:27:37,272
Thank you for watching.

548
00:27:37,307 --> 00:27:39,925
If you want more stories
about the hidden machinery

549
00:27:39,960 --> 00:27:41,399
that quietly runs our money,

550
00:27:41,434 --> 00:27:44,052
and our lives, this is
what this channel does.

551
00:27:44,087 --> 00:27:46,705
Subscribe, and we will see you in the next

552
00:27:46,740 --> 00:27:47,460
one.
